			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">E3: EQ2 
<br />

<br />
Alright, you would think being the premier Everquest 2 website on the internet, we wouldn’t have had much of a problem scooping up some EQ2 info this E3 right? Wrong. Not that it was SOE’s fault, to be honest when they figured out who we were they went out of their way to be extremely accommodating but due to our own inexperience, it wasn’t as easy to find some time with the totally booked EQ2 guys as we would’ve thought. 
<br />

<br />
As you already know, we introduced ourselves that Tuesday, and myself and two others were allowed a short entrance into the SOE lair, where we were given a few short moments to spend some illicit time with what was possibly the most impressive looking game at the entire E3 show. John Blakely (Senior Producer of EQ2) was extremely gracious with his time, and managed to answer a few questions before it was time for us to go. This little event resulted in the post I made from E3, as well as a properly scheduled meeting on Friday afternoon at 12:30. 
<br />

<br />
From here on smooth sailing right? I hate to break it to you, but it was nothing but turbulence for your EQ2 crew. On Friday when we went back, being the nondescript sort that we were, I’m afraid nobody recognized us. It is nobody’s fault but our own, because as we’re all writers for the EQiis parent website, <a href="http://www.gamewatchers.net" target="_blank">www.gamewatchers.net</a>, that is how we introduced ourselves that friday. After some curious glances being cast in our direction, with the underlying thoughts of “who the hell are these guys?” we were ushered into the Sony booth. 
<br />

<br />
Admittedly, I think the three of us who entered the booth that Friday, were a bit on edge, being surrounded by possibly the mecca of MMOGs (Planetside, EQ, EQoA, EQ2, LoEQ) we said nothing. And so unsure of what we were there for, we were moved over to the Planetside section. This wasn’t bad for me, as I’ve been playing Planetside of late and had a bunch of questions anyways, but as that wasn’t what we were there for, it may have not been the best use of our time. After that, it seemed nobody was sure what to do with us, so because we had seen part of the EQ2 demo two days earlier, and everybody else was booked up, we were prepared to be ushered out. 
<br />

<br />
It was at this point, filled with the unholy fear of what you guys would undoubtedly do to us if we came back with no EQ2 info at all (I believe we figured it had something to do with pitchforks and torches), Onyx, DevilDancer and myself decided that we either figure out a way to get info there and then, or else we might as well paste on a mustache, rename ourselves Jose, and head south in a ’72 VW van (awww yeah). So possibly, knowing no other option was open to us, we pleaded to see somebody (anybody) for just a minute or two who could answer a few of our questions about EQ2. 
<br />

<br />
Possibly fate was smiling on us, or massive coincidence clicked in our direction, but either way, we were told that we would have five minutes with an EQ2 developer. While it wasn’t much, we thought “hey, anything that can prevent a lynching is good with us”. 
<br />

<br />
Lo and behold, who comes out to talk to us? None other than Bill Trost (Lead Designer of EQ2) himself. This time, fearing that we would get little time with him as it was, we introduced ourselves as the guys who ran the EQ2 website. Perhaps this was a smart move on our part, as suddenly it seemed his interest in talking to us greatly increased. He was excited about the game, we were excited about the game, and it was great to talk to somebody who really knew what was going on. It was also great to hear him say that “they all read the site every day”. 
<br />

<br />
After that, it was an easy ride. I whipped out my notebook with a few questions we had prepared from general questions you guys seemed to have, and got right into it. The first question I wanted to know was whether, combat classes would have any ability to participate in tradeskills at all. As anybody who played EQ1 knows, any class could pick up a tradeskill whenever they wanted, and it sometimes would allow you to have a change of pace from anything that was feeling repetitive or monotonous. Bill explained that at this time, they were keeping the tradeskill abilities completely separate from the combat classes, but proceeded to mention that the tradeskill classes would severely lack combat skills. Making the world a far more dangerous place for them to traverse alone. 
<br />

<br />
In EQ2 there will be a large focus on making the tradeskill classes an integral part of the Everquest world, where relationships will form by people being dependant upon tradeskills, and tradeskills being dependant upon the combat classes. This way, if you decide to pursue the non-confrontational path as a tradeskill class, you will not find yourself feeling useless or unwanted in Norrath, but instead provide integral services to players as you work on your own form of advancement. While not much was said about the tradeskill classes in specific, nor the tradeskills themselves, Bill assured us that it was far more entertaining then hitting a ‘combine button’ and was excited to describe the tradeskill system as “robust”. 
<br />

<br />
After that, I asked about housing. We all knew it was in the feature list, but everybody wanted to know what was in it for them? The benefits of housing. It was great to hear Bill explain that housing would indeed provide more benefits than just looks. In EQ2 there will be two types of housing. Player housing and Guild Housing. While player housing will be open to everybody, and far more accessible, he explained that Guild Housing would indeed have limited availability. So yes, there will be a land rush for Guild Housing, it is meant to be a rare thing, a prestigious thing even. It will be expensive, and hard to get. The best spots will be the most coveted spots, and chances are you’ll know each and every guild who resides in those spots. Bill managed to get whoever was running the demo, to take us outside the demo for a few moments and show us an example of Guild Housing though. I hate to drool in front of people, but to hell with thee, I was impressed. The Guild Housing looks great. There will not be huge amounts of customization to the Guild Halls, as opposed to the Players Housing which will allow more character customization, but the Guild Halls will be mostly unique, designed by the EQ artists especially for that purpose. I know you all want to know whether you’ll be able to design your own guild banners, etc, etc, well I didn’t think to ask. But I can tell you right now the predesigned Guild Halls look exactly like they should look. They are massive in size, and magnificent in design. Immersion is something EQ has always managed to do better than most other MMOGs and it does not look like they have any intention of stopping with EQ2. 
<br />

<br />
As for Player Housing, and its benefits. There is one thing about EQ2 that is very different than EQ1, which is that storage is a valuable commodity. You will not have the same ease of a universal bank that you were used to having in EQ1. Because this is a big deal, it places an immediate benefit on Player Housing, as it increases your storage space. While this is the primary benefit of player housing, Tradeskills classes will also be able to place tradeskill utensils within their home, giving player houses but another use. Whether we’ll see more benefits in the future is yet to be known, but due to the changed mechanic of storage space, the importance of Player Housing becomes immediately apparent. 
<br />

<br />
Now, I’d apologize for Bill’s sanity, as I’m afraid I flitted from subject to subject like a hummingbird on speed. I wanted to get as much information as possible, so was asking what I deemed to be the most pertinent questions first, and then moving to whatever question struck my fancy, rather than numerically moving through my notebook as I’d planned. Because of this, the next thing I asked about was raiding and the high end game. Let’s face it, if you’ve played EQ, you know all about raids, and if you haven’t played EQ, you probably know about raids anyways, as it was such a large part of EQ. 
<br />

<br />
To my surprise, Bill looked at me with surprise, as if I had said something strange. Then as if deciphering a foreign language, he nodded sagaciously, and went on to explain that while “in Everquest, raiding and the high end game were synonymous with each other”, Everquest 2 no longer saw them that way. “Raiding is fun” he explained, “why should you only be able to do it in the high levels?” In EQ2, expect to see raidable content at all stages of the game. This means if you want to have a guild, and participate in the exciting battles, and the organization of it all, you won’t be forced to just be a power gamer that is competing in the high end game for all of the same content. Instead, you might just raid once a week, hang out with your friends the rest of the week, and enjoy your progression through the game at a leisurely pace. Of course you may already be jumping to conclusions, but won’t everybody be fighting over the same raidable content? The high levels are bad enough in EQ, won’t it be that much worse with everybody raiding at any level? 
<br />

<br />
No. This is where we get into Everquest, and that word that causes so much controversy, instancing. Everquest 2 will use instancing sparsely, so do not worry that you will always really only be playing with six players as you instance one zone and another zone and another. But EQ will implement instancing to make sure that players don’t find themselves struggling for the same content over and over again. Instancing will also allow far more detailed scripted events to be carried out. We saw an example of this during the E3 demo, when the camera was moving through Nektropos Castle, to a courtyard where Nagafen was fighting (this isn’t necessarily where Nagafen will be, this was a scripted demo remember). While the camera was moving through the hall, the tunnel would shake from pounding, and debris would sift down through the air. Now obviously, with this type of personal experience, unless you wanted to create something that was only able to be triggered once, you can’t do this sort of thing. With instancing though, used in special cases, far more personal scripts will be able to be carried out, bringing the immersion that much more to life. 
<br />

<br />
While in general I don’t like instancing (I enjoy the competition, and hustle and bustle of a well crowded dungeon) I do see an immense value of instancing certain encounters to really bring them to life for the players, also too many raids forces from overlapping each other, especially in the lower levels. It is hard to truly visualize how this will work in action, but if they can recreate the sort of experience that I saw during the demo, I will certainly give instancing a fair shot. 
<br />

<br />
At this point in time, as I’m sure you can imagine, our five minutes was long up, but we were having such a great time grilling Bill for info, I don’t think anybody noticed it. From instancing, I asked about travel. In the original release of Everquest, travel was slow. In my opinion this added something to the game, but that is just my opinion. Since then, as Everquest has been progressing with expansion after expansion, and lately with the introduction of the Nexus, travel time has been cut down considerably. I was curious whether we could expect to see the same sort of thing in Everquest 2. The answer we received was interesting double fold. The first thing Bill told us was that ships are not meant as travel devices in Everquest 2. While we didn’t ask about ships directly, we all knew it existed on the feature list and were excited to hear more. In Everquest 2, ships will have their own gameplay uses for adventuring. In other words, yes, you will be able to be a pirate if that is your desire. Now the exact mechanics that will go into this sort of thing remain a mystery to me, but the idea of being able to buy a ship and explore oceans in search of new land or other ships excites me. I want to be able to sail and adventure with a boat. I’m not sure how that will work, but it seemed like it was important to the EQ2 devs. Important enough that unfortunately, mounts will not make it into the original release feature list. Personally, while I like mounts and all, I’d far rather prefer the ability to sail a boat then to simply ride a horse to speed up travel. Don’t think there will never be mounts in EQ2 though; they will surely be included at some point in time, just not at release. 
<br />

<br />
Of course my real question about travel had not been answered yet. Would travel be that greatly changed? Well, from what we were told, ports in general will be spread out over a far larger range of classes (stop weeping Druids and Wizards, it’s not the end of the world) but evacs and the emergency type of portal spells will still remain more class specific. Really, this only makes perfect sense, with 48 classes, to leave only a few classes with general travel spells, could potentially lead to a huge problem if nobody wanted to play those classes. At least this way, with something as important as ports, we can be sure we won’t be left running on foot when we want to get from Freeport to Qeynos just because Druids and Wizards suck. Personally I expect to see this type of thing a lot more in EQ2. The main, core class type abilities that are considered ‘needed’ should be spread out more evenly, while the special class specific abilities should remain unique to a class. This way classes can be individualized, but you stay away from the holy ‘trinity’ group archetype. 
<br />

<br />
Jumping from subject to subject with no rhyme or reason we proceeded to get into the item decay issue, and Bill had no problem getting right into it with us. Now while Bill talked about it in what I considered some fairly impressive detail, I’m man enough to admit that he confused the hell out of me. So while I think there was a lot of information given, I didn’t really understand the half of it, so can only talk about the little I did know. 
<br />

<br />
From my understanding, all items will decay. Tradesman will be the only ones able to repair this decay (yes, this is another thing you will need tradesmen for). Now the question is, how things decay, why they decay, and how that will effect the game. This is where I got confused. From my understanding, items will belong to a variety of tiers (whether they will be visibly marked in a tier or not, I don’t know), what tier they belong in will depend on the rarity and type of item. Higher tiered items, thus being rarer, will decay slower. The question is whether there will be other variables that affect the rate of decay, I believe there may be, and I believe Bill explained whether there was or not, but I can’t say I really understood. All I got is that item decay will be a part of the game, another mechanic helpful in keeping the economy from stagnating, as well as another reason to have a lot of tradesman as friends. How this will all work in practice I’m not sure, but I am excited to find out. Either way, don’t sweat too much, the epic weapon you’ve spent a month questing on isn’t going to decay like that steel sword you looted off the rotten Frogluk, and in my opinion that’s important. 
<br />

<br />
Ironically enough, after being confused by the complexity of the item decay, the next thing I asked about was Everquest 2’s complexity. I play a lot of MMOGs and have seen a diabolical trend that seems to be turning these games into crap. That trend is to dumb the game down. Take away anything that a player might possibly figure out a way to be innovative with. Remove individual player abilities to make sure that everybody is a balanced evenly. Half of the fun I had in Everquest was challenging the game and myself in the process. Looking at my classes abilities, or the abilities of myself and one or two others and wondering “how can we kill that dragon?”, “how will we get out of a bind of things go wrong?”, etc. In other words, how can we use the abilities given to us in creative ways to do things we probably shouldn’t be able to do? 
<br />

<br />
I demand complexity in a game, I demand the ability to be able to really challenge myself. Everquest had that (in the first two expansions anyways), but I have seen very few games willing to be that daring. Bill’s answer to this was one that greatly reassured me. Everquest 2 will be an extremely complex game in the high levels, he explained, but a goal of the EQ2 team is to keep that complexity in tact in the main portion of the game, but provide a more accessible game to any who would be interested in trying it, without immediately overwhelming them. This is as worthy a goal as any in my opinion. Everquest did overwhelm me when I started, a little more than I would’ve liked (I put all my stat points into agi/sta and I was a pure caster. As you can imagine I regretted it a bit in the high levels). But to have a game where the beginning learning curve is a bit softer for anybody starting out, but can still remain challenging for those really into it, if accomplished will be a great thing indeed. So if you feared the ‘dumbing down of EQ’ as much as I did, from what I heard and saw, I’d say that we have nothing to fear. 
<br />

<br />
At this point in time, I think Bill might’ve actually been leaving a few other appointments waiting patiently for him, but we got some more info anyways (Thanks Bill!). Next we talked a bit about quest. I remember asking fairly specifically “Will you have dynamic quests?”, now admittedly this is a terrible question. Really how much more vague could I get? I wouldn’t know how to answer it if somebody hoisted it upon me without any more information. Bill just blinked once or twice and then said with a smile “yes”. I’ve got to say it was a great thing to hear. We talked about it a bit, and revealed that while we wouldn’t see quests change the physical world itself, we wouldn’t definitely see changes in the political and social climate of Norrath. Plus, the quest system is far deeper and more intense overall. With the evolution of Everquest we saw quests go from things such as Soulfire, to the Epic quests, to the key quests, to the Ring War and so on. Expect to see EQ2 continue with that evolution. More story, more scripts, more content. I couldn’t be more excited about it. 
<br />

<br />
At this point, Bill had spent as much time as he could with us, and had other pressing engagements, but he did say that we could expect to see a Beta this summer, and that yes, eventually there would be an open beta (so all of those who want to play in beta so much, your chance should come). He then left us, but not before we asked the Dev running the demo, whether EQ2 was looking to be on schedule. He assured us, that it was, so despite Blackguards April Fool’s joke, we’re still looking for a Winter 2003 release. 
<br />

<br />
This is the majority of information we gained. I may have missed some things, and some things may be inaccurate (I was scribbling notes furiously), but all in all, the only thing left to give are my own personal thoughts. 
<br />

<br />
I saw EQ2 on the first day of E3. It was the first MMOG I saw, and I was impressed. After that, during my time at E3 I had a chance to look at nearly every other MMOG before my second showing of EQ2. I saw Dragon Empires, Horizons, World of Warcraft, Lineage II, City of Heroes, Uru: Ages Beyond Myst, Final Fantasy Online, Dark and Light, Star Wars Galaxies (very briefly this one), Mythica and probably a few other MMOGs I can’t think of off the top of my head. Then I saw EQ2 again. I don’t want to come off sounding crazy by any means, but EQ2 really did floor me when I saw it again, and compared it to everything else I had seen. It was beautiful, majestic and huge. 
<br />

<br />
When I logged into Everquest for the first time, I felt some magic, as I found myself immersed in a fantasy world. I thought that it was simply a side effect of my first MMOG that a seriously played. When I watched the EQ2 demo, I felt a little of that again. I felt as if I were looking at a world rather than a game. I’m not entirely sure if I can explain why, personally I think it has something to do with the EQ/EQ2 design style. Possibly the size of things, or the city and zone design. I don’t honestly know, but I know when I looked at the EQ2 graphics, and saw a door that I swore was wood, and saw rock walls of a dungeon that were cracked and dirty, I was more impressed by it than any other MMOG I saw. I can’t speak for the gameplay yet, all I can speak of are the graphics and the little bit of world design that I saw, but for what I saw, I was amazed and impressed at once. 
<br />

<br />
And for that feeling, and the time to talk about many of the questions that you, the community posed, I greatly thank the SOE EQ2 team, Bill Trost and John Blakely especially (and Tamara Sanderson for managing to set it all up). Thanks again guys, it was appreciated.<br />_________________<br /><img src="http://gormsplace.homestead.com/files/MACARONI.Gif" border="0" /></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
